SIMPLE: smash
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Smash
<hw>Smash</hw> <pr>(sm⟦acr⟧sh)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Smashed</conjf> <pr>(sm⟦acr⟧sht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Smashing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Sw.
<ets>smisk</ets> a blow, stroke, <ets>smiska</ets> to strike, dial. Sw.
<ets>smaske</ets> to kiss with a noise, and E. <ets>smack</ets> a loud
kiss, a slap.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To break in pieces by violence; to
dash to pieces; to crush.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here everything is broken and <qex>smashed</qex> to pieces.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Lawn Tennis)</fld> <def>To hit (the ball) from
above the level of the net with a very hard overhand stroke.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smash</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Smash
<hw>Smash</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To break up, or to pieces
suddenly, as the result of collision or pressure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smash</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Smash
<hw>Smash</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A breaking or dashing to
pieces; utter destruction; wreck.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, bankruptcy.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smasher</ent>⟦br⟧
